.TH _PRINTF 3 "Nov 25" "Holberton School" "Library Functions Manual"

.SH NAME
_printf \- produce output according to a format

.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
#include "main.h"

int _printf(const char *format, ...);
.fi

.SH DESCRIPTION
the 
.B _printf()
function produces formatted output to the standard output stream (stdout).
It behaves similarly to the standard C library function
.B printf ,
but supports a limited set of conversion specifiers as part of the Holberton School project requirements


The
.I format
string consists of ordinary characters, which are printed as-is, and convension specifiers beginning with the '%' character

The following conversion specifiers are supported:

.TP
.B %c
prints a single character

.TP
.B %s
prints a string 
If the passed pointer is NULL, the string "(null)" is printed

.TP
.B %d
prints a single decimal integer

.TP
.B %i
prints a signed decimal integer (same as %d)

.TP
.B %%
prints a litiral percent sign '%'

.TP
The function does
.B NOT
handle the following features:

.IP \(bu 2
Flag characters (+, space, #, 0, -)

.IP \(bu 2
Field width

.IP \(bu 2
Precision

.IP \(bu 2
Length modifiers (h, l, etc.)

.PP
If the
.I format
string is NULL, or if it contains an incomplete conversion specifier (such as a trailing '%' at the end of the string)
.B -1
is returned

.SH RETURN VALUE 
The function returns the total number of characters printed (excluding the terminating null byte)
On failure, such as invalid or incomplete format strings, the function returns 
.B -1

.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
_printf("Hello %s!\\n", "World");
       output: Hello World!

_printf("Character: %c\\n", 'H');
       output: Character: H

_printf("Number: %d\\n", 1024);
       output: 1024

_printf("Use %% to print a percent sign.\\n");
       output: Use % to print a percent sign

_printf("Complete the sentence: you %s nothing, John Snow.\\n", (char *)0);
       output: Complete the sentence: you (null) nothing, John Snow
.fi

